value.value: An anatomical projection ventral to the glenoid fossa on the scapulocoracoid that abuts on the cliethrum (if present).

definition.value: Can exist in taxa without a cleithrum.

value.value: The transverse pelvic ridge is a short crest directly anterior to, and not extending posterior to, the prominent supra-acetabular buttress  from Pawley and Warren 2006.
Joint that articulates left and right clavicles.
Caudal fin lepidotrichium located ventral to the notochord.
A distinct bony ridge on ventralsurface of the humeral shaft that corresponds to the attachment site of the pectoralis muscle.
A centrale found in the pes.
Flange present of the distal region of the humerus, associated with extensor musculature of forelimb.
Surface of a long bone that possess the flexor muscle attachment sites.
Projection on the lateral side of proximal part of the ulna.
The medial most digits of the pes.

definition.value: In most tetrapods this corresponds to digits II-IV, but the exact identiy of digits in this region varies taxonomically based on digit numbering.

value.value: Medial facing projection or surface on the anterior ( cranial) region of the cleithrum that is often textured or denticled. This process has two primary functions: 1) its shape enhances the vertical strength of the cleithrum and 2) it forms the edge of the gill chamber and helps to direct water after it has passed over the gills (modified from Clack 2012).
An enlargement of the distal region of the calcaneum that corresponds to the attachment site for the foot extensor muscles.
Process on ilium located anteriorly to acetabulum.
Fossa on the medial surface on the scapula above the glenoid.
Osteological unit consisting of the astragalus and calcaneum.
Narrow bone that lies ventral to the level of insertion of the pectoral fin and is sutured to the posterior edges of both the clavicle and cleithrum. Based on Forey 1998.

definition.value: The presence of this bone is a synapomorphy of coelacanth fishes.

value.value: A dorsal fin located anterior to posterior dorsal fin.
Flattened process of the dorsl surface of the astragalus which contacts the tibia anteriorly.
Foramen that perforates supraglenoid buttress.
A bony projection dorsal to the glenoid articulation on the scapulocoracoid.

definition.value: In basal tetrapodomorphs this structure braces the scapula on the cleithrum, but this function is lost in derived tetrapods.

value.value: A prominent ridge in basal tetrapods on the ventral side of the femur that includes the fourth trochater, internal trochanter and the adductor crest (based on Coates, 1996).
A bony crest on venteral side of femur that is the attachment site for the adductor muscles.
Raised surface at the posterior portion of the acetabulum (see Nesbitt, 2011).

Muscle that is associated with tail flexion. Orginates on one of the first post sacral vertebrae posteriorly and inserts on the posterior edge of the m.puboischiotibialis. (modified from Duellman and Trueb 1994).

definition.value: To Do: add attachment site terms to ext

value.value: Expanded and flattened ventral region of clavicle bone.
Expanded dorsal region of the cleithrum.
Longitudnal bony ridge on tibia, attachment site of the major extensor muscle of the hind limb.

A boney projection on the internal diaphysis of the femur anterior or medial to the intertrochanteric fossa, below the femoral head. Muscle attachment site for ventral muscle mass notably the puboischiofemoralis externus. Modified from Romer 1956.
A bony process that corresponds to the attachment site for the forelimb supinator muscles in tetrapods, distal to the deltopectoral crest and anterior to the radial condyle.
A marked depression on the medial side of the scapula blade, often opposite the glenoid region.

A bony protuberance dorsal to the acetabulum on the ilium, confluent with the supraacetabular crest (when present). Acts as a bone brace to prevent excessive femoral abduction and the origin site for part of the M. iliofemoralis.
Anatomical process located in the proximal region of the coracoid in avian theropods, that is hook-shaped.

The palmar aponeurosis is a fibrotendinous complex that functions as the tendinous extension of the palmaris longus, when present, and as a strong stabilizing structure for the palmar skin of the hand. It has five longitudinal slips that project into the base of each digit and a deeper transverse portion that crosses the palm at the proximal end of the metacarpals bones (from Wikipedia).
Anatomical projection on the ilium, anchoring caudal muscles.
Fossa located on the brevis shelf.

label.value: articular surface for the calcaneum on the astragalus

value.value: Contact surface between the calcaneum and the astragalus located on the astragalus.

label.value: articular surface for the astragalus on the calcaneum

value.value: Contact surface between the calcaneum and the astragalus located on the calcaneum.
The astragalo-calcaneal canal forms a foramen between the articulated astragalus and calcaneum when the canal is ossified (Nesbitt, 2011).
Morphological structure denoting the extent of an attachment site for a soft tissue on a skeletal element.
Anatomical projection that is an expansion on the proximal region of the humerus.

definition.value: Origin of the aponeursis of humeral head of the M. biceps brachii. From Bamuel et al. 1993

value.value: A sesamoid found in the found in the ligamentum calcanei of a wide variety of frogs. (based on Nussbaum, R. A. 1982.
A cup shaped articular surface on a bone.
A notch or opening in the ventral part of the acetabular rim.
Tuberosity on the posterior surface of the lateral femoral condyle.
An internally and externally symmetrical tail (caudal) fin.

definition.value: In Dipnoi, may be secondarily acquired from the homocercal condition by loss of the real caudal fin and the gaining of a new one from dorsal and anal elements, e.g. in Gadidae. http://www.briancoad.com/Complete%20Dictionary%20latest%20version.htm

value.value: Type of tail (caudal) fin in which the vertebral column turns upwards into the upper lobe which is longer than the lower. Asymmetrical externally as well as internally.

definition.value: Elasmobranchii, Acipenseridae, Polyodontidae and in many larval Teleostomi. May also be used for an asymmetrical caudal fin but with epicercal defining upper lobe longer and hypocercal the lower lobe longer. http://www.briancoad.com/dictionary/DicPics/heterorercal.htm

value.value: Type of tail fin in which the vertebrae generally turn upward at the hind end of the column, but which is externally symmetrical. The fin rays of the caudal are supported by hypaxial elements.
Type of tail fin where the lower lobe is the longer and is supported by the vertebral column. Asymmetrical externally as well as internally.
Formen present on the ectepicondyle of the humerus.
Tail fin in which the the caudal part of the notochord tapers posterodorsally. Based on Pradel et al. 2007.

definition.value: Osteostracans are the only jawless vertebrates that share with gnathostomes an epicercal tail.
